
[1]behold

   BEHO'LD, v.t. pret. and pp. beheld' [L.observo, from servo, to keep.]

   1. To fix the eyes upon; to see with attention; to observe with care.

   Behold the lamb of God which taketh away the sin of the world. John 1.

   2. In a less intensive sense, to look upon; to see.

   When he beheld the serpent of brass, he lived. Num. 21.

           BEHO'LD, v.i. To look; to direct the eyes to an object.

   And I beheld, and lo, in the midst of the throne, a lamb,as it had been
   slain. Rev.5.

   1. To fix the attention upon an object; to attend; to direct or fix the
   mind.

   Behold, I stand at the door and knock. Rev.3.word is much used in this
   manner for exciting attention, or admiration. It is in the imperative
   mode, expressing command, or exhortation; and by no means a mere
   exclamation.
